lucas(js210)  3 days ago
Hey y’all! Apologies about the google meet getting cut off. But @Andrew Thresher (RB129) solved the LSMan problem, here’s his solution:
module Flightable
  def fly
    puts "I am #{@name}, I am a #{self.class.to_s.downcase}, and I can fly!"
  end
end

class Superhero  
  attr_accessor :ability
  
  include Flightable
  
  def self.fight_crime
    puts "I am #{self}!"
    me = LSMan.new("myself")
    me.ability = Ability.new("coding skills")
    me.announce_ability
  end
  
  def initialize(name)
    @name = name
  end
  
  def announce_ability
    puts "I fight crime with my #{ability.description} ability!"
  end
end

class LSMan < Superhero; end

class Ability
  attr_reader :description

  def initialize(description)
    @description = description
  end
end

superman = Superhero.new('Superman')
superman.fly # => I am Superman, I am a superhero, and I can fly!
LSMan.fight_crime 
# => I am LSMan!
# => I fight crime with my coding skills ability!

Guys a quick question.
I was toying with the code that @Aryan Binazir gave as an example. In the original code we got an error when we attempted to call the private method value on an external object house 2 passed into the instance method >(other_method) as an argument.when i wrapped the private method value in a public method current_value and called this method on >(other_house) then we get the state of the instance variable @value.  I am trying to understand this but I am not able to get a clear picture. Can someone explain what is going on here. Also in this example would the object house2 be classed as a collaborator object though they are from the same class.  Apologies for the vague explanation, still getting my head around it. Thanks in advance guys.
# How is Method Access Control implemented in Ruby? Provide examples of when we would use public, protected, and private access modifiers.

class House
  attr_reader :name
  
  def initialize(name, owner, value)
    @name = name
    @owner = owner
    @value = value
  end
  
  def house_owner
    owner
  end
  
  def >(other_house)
    value > other_house.current_value
  end
  
  def current_value
    value
  end
  
  private
  
  attr_reader :value

  attr_reader :owner
end

house1 = House.new('house1', 'Jose', 100000)
house2 = House.new('house2', 'Josh', 80000)

puts "House 1 is more expensive" if house1 > house2

p house1.current_value

p house1.>(house2)

#=> House 1 is more expensive
#=> 100000
#=> true

@riaz I may struggle to explain over text. Happy to meet up and explain over Zoom if nobody else is able to articulate why it works well. house2 would not be a collaborator to house1 , also happy to explain that over Zoom.
lucas(js210)  3 days ago
Hey @riaz, so I might not have a totally thorough technical answer, but I’m going to give this my best shot. This is really interesting code! I’d never thought to expose a private method to a public method and then use that public method for comparison.Essentially though, you’ve created a nice workaround to private methods not being able to be used for comparison. The original getter method is still private, but private methods can be called from public methods within the class, so when you call current_value, it returns the value of instance variable @value. The getter method is still private, however it doesn’t really matter once you use the public method current_value , as it is a public method, and therefore can be used for comparison. You’ve essentially made the private method value public with current_value, if that makes sense. It still stands though that private methods can’t be used for comparisons, because if you used the private value reader in your > method, it would raise an error.
def >(other_house)
    value > other_house.current_value
  end
  
  def current_value
    value
  end
  
  private
  
  attr_reader :value

  attr_reader :owner
end
As far as your question about collaborators, no, as @Aryan Binazir pointed out, house2 is not a collaborator because it is not a part of house1 ’s state. Here’s an article that explains collaborator objects well.Hope this cleared some things up, or at the very least @Aryan Binazir can clear stuff up later on Zoom. It can be challenging to explain this stuff over text. (edited)
